owerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig17e.jpeg" height="1280" width="1008" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17e</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig17e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig18.jpeg" height="767" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span> Chart shows variants in CS morphology. A normal CS is usually 2–5 cm in length <i>(L)</i> and 6–14 mm in diameter <i>(D).</i> The CS is normally larger during ventricular systole and contracts during atrial systole. It is usually tubular or “windsock” in shape and gently curved toward the LA. (Data are from references <a href="#r6" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r6">6</a>, <a href="#r35" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r35">35</a>, <a href="#r51" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r51">51</a>, <a href="#r60" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r60">60</a>, <a href="#r61" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r61">61</a>.) <i>AF</i> = atrial fibrillation, <i>ASD</i> = atrial septal defect, <i>AV</i> = arteriovenous, <i>AVNRT</i> = atrioventricular node reentrant tachycardia, <i>ccTGA</i> = congenital corrected transposition of the great arteries, <i>CHD</i> = congenital heart disease, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava, <i>TF</i> = tetralogy of Fallot.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure