iv class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig25a.jpeg" height="944" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig25a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig25b.jpeg" height="989" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig25b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig25c.jpeg" height="1183" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig25c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig25d.jpeg" height="1236" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25d</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig25d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig26a.jpeg" height="1103" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig26a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig26b.jpeg" height="1079" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig26b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig27a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1045" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig27a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig27b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1106" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig27b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig28.jpeg" height="1234" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig28" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28</span> Anatomy of CS musculature is shown in this drawing of the posterior view of the heart. The origin of the CS can be identified by the opening of the oblique vein of Marshall <i>(OVM)</i> externally or the valve of Vieussens <i>(VV)</i> internally. The CS is surrounded by a sleeve of myocardium, a remnant of the sinus venosus musculature, which is continuous with muscle of the RA wall (CS-RA muscle continuity). This CS muscle sleeve normally stops abruptly at or shortly beyond the orifices of the entering coronary veins, where it may thicken in a sphincterlike fashion. In normal hearts, bridging myocardial fibers are seen between the CS and LA walls (CS-LA connection) (star). These CS-LA muscle connections can be the source of atrial fibrillation recurrence after pulmonary vein isolation. <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava, <i>LMV</i> = left marginal vein, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>PV</i> = posterior vein, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava, <i>ThV</i> = thebesian valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig28">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig29a.jpeg" height="707" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig29a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig29b.jpeg" height="678" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig29b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig30a.jpeg" height="1089" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig30a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig30b.jpeg" height="1094" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig30b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig30c.jpeg" height="1159" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig30c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig30d.jpeg" height="1163" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30d</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig30d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig31.jpeg" height="1279" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig31" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31</span> Volume-rendered and endoscopic CT (inset) images show the relationship between the posterior mitral ring and the CS. The left circumflex artery <i>(LCx)</i> courses adjacent to the superior commissure, and the CS is adjacent to the inferior margin of the mitral ring. These vessels can be damaged during surgical or percutaneous mitral valve interventions. When the circumflex artery is dominant, the entire attachment of the posterior leaflet of the mitral valve may be closely related to this artery. <i>AA</i> = ascending aorta, <i>L</i> = left CS, <i>P</i> = posterior CS, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig31">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig32a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig32a.jpeg" height="1154" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 32a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig32a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig32b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig32b.jpeg" height="1128" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 32b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig32b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig33a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig33a.jpeg" height="1280" width="877" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 33a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig33a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig33b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.321115014/asset/images/115014fig33b.jpeg" height="1280" width="922" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 33b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.321115014&amp;id=fig33b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Anderson RH, Brown NA, Moorman AF. Development and structures of the venous pole of the heart. <em>Dev Dyn</em> 2006;235(1):2–9.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1002/dvdy.20578">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16193508/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Development+and+structures+of+the+venous+pole+of+the+heart&amp;author=RH+Anderson&amp;author=NA+Brown&amp;author=AF+Moorman&amp;publication_year=2006&amp;journal=Dev+Dyn&amp;pag